General rules:
- Include only tags, patterns, smells, and safety-concerns that actually apply. Omit keys with empty collections.
- :segments should list the major definitions, not every helper. Cap at 20 segments.
- Keep :summary and :purpose each under 500 characters.

File-level field guidelines:

:summary — one paragraph plain-English overview of what this file does. Focus on behavior and responsibilities, not implementation details. Under 500 chars.
:purpose — why this file exists and its role in the project. What would break or be missing without it? Under 500 chars.

:tags — semantic concerns present in this file. Only include tags that actually apply:
  :io — reads/writes files, streams, or devices.
  :parsing — transforms text/binary into structured data.
  :concurrency — threads, locks, channels, async coordination.
  :configuration — reads/manages config, env vars, feature flags.
  :testing — test definitions, fixtures, mocks, assertions.
  :networking — HTTP, sockets, RPC, protocol handling.
  :validation — input checking, schema validation, constraint enforcement.
  :logging — log output, audit trails, structured logging.
  :security — auth, crypto, access control, secrets management.
  :routing — URL dispatch, request routing, path matching.
  :middleware — request/response pipeline, interceptors, decorators.
  :state-management — stateful stores, caches, atoms, refs, session management.

:complexity — overall cognitive complexity of this file:
  :trivial — boilerplate, constants, re-exports. No logic.
  :simple — straightforward linear code, minimal branching.
  :moderate — some branching and state, but understandable.
  :complex — significant branching, multiple interacting concerns.
  :very-complex — deeply nested logic, complex state machines, hard to follow.

:patterns — design patterns used in this file. Only include if clearly present:
  :state-machine — explicit state transitions based on events/input.
  :producer-consumer — one component generates work, another processes it.
  :builder — step-by-step construction of complex objects.
  :factory — creates instances based on parameters without exposing creation logic.
  :decorator — wraps functionality to add behavior transparently.
  :adapter — converts one interface to another.
  :pipeline — data flows through a chain of transformation stages.
  :ring-handler — Clojure Ring-style request->response handler.
  :middleware-chain — composable wrappers around a core handler.

:layer — architectural layer this file belongs to:
  :core — fundamental domain logic, algorithms, data structures.
  :subsystem — cohesive internal module (e.g., scheduler, cache, parser).
  :driver — adapter to external systems (DB, filesystem, network, APIs).
  :api — external-facing interface (HTTP endpoints, CLI, public API surface).
  :util — general-purpose helpers with no domain knowledge.

:category — domain role of this file:
  :backend — server-side logic, API handlers, business rules, data processing.
  :frontend — UI components, rendering, DOM manipulation, client-side logic.
  :infrastructure — CI/CD, Docker, deploy scripts, cloud/platform config.
  :configuration — app config files, env setup, feature flags, settings.
  :data — schemas, migrations, seeds, ORM/DB models, data definitions.
  :testing — tests, test helpers, fixtures, mocks.
  :documentation — doc generators, examples, API docs.
  :tooling — build scripts, linters, code generators, dev utilities.
  :shared — cross-cutting libraries used across multiple layers or domains.

:confidence — your self-assessed confidence that this analysis is accurate (0.0-1.0). Lower if the file is obfuscated, generated, or in an unfamiliar domain.

:dependencies — list of namespace/module/package names this file imports, requires, or uses. Include only direct dependencies. Use the canonical import name (e.g. \"clojure.string\", \"react\", \"os\", \"datomic.client.api\"). Omit if none.

Segment field guidelines:

:kind definitions:
  :function — standalone function (defn, def, fn, func). :method — member of a class/struct/impl.
  :class — class definition. :interface — Java/C#/Go/TS interface. :trait — Rust/Scala/PHP trait. :protocol — Clojure protocol.
  :macro — compile-time code generation. :multimethod — Clojure multimethod.
  :record — Clojure record or similar value type. :type — type alias or newtype. :struct — C/Go/Rust struct.
  :enum — enumeration. :union — C/C++ union, Rust enum with data, TS discriminated union.
  :typedef — C typedef, Go type alias. :constant — const, final static, #define, def of a fixed value.
  :property — getter/setter/computed property. :module — Python/Ruby/Elixir module (not namespace).
  :namespace — namespace/package declaration. :global — mutable global/static state. :include — import/require/include statement.

:args — parameter list in source syntax. Clojure: [x y]. Java: (int x, String y). Omit for kinds with no params.
:returns — return type if the language uses explicit return types. Omit for Clojure, Python without annotations, etc.

:visibility — access level. Map language conventions to these values:
  :public — accessible everywhere (Java public, Go Capitalized, Rust pub, Python no prefix).
  :private — accessible only within defining scope (Java private, Go lowercase, Clojure ^:private, Python _prefix).
  :protected — accessible in subclasses (Java/C++/C# protected).
  :internal — accessible within module/crate/assembly (C# internal, Rust pub(crate), Kotlin internal).
  :package — accessible within package only (Java default access).

:docstring — the doc comment text (Javadoc, Python docstring, Clojure docstring, /// comments, JSDoc). Omit if none.
:deprecated — true only if explicitly marked (@Deprecated, #[deprecated], ^:deprecated, @obsolete). Omit if not deprecated.

:complexity — per-segment cognitive complexity:
  :trivial — simple delegation, constant, or 1-2 line accessor.
  :simple — straightforward logic, one code path, no branching.
  :moderate — some branching or iteration, manageable.
  :complex — multiple nested branches, complex state transitions, hard to reason about.

:smells — only include if actually present:
  :deep-nesting — 3+ levels of nested control flow.
  :too-many-params — more than 4-5 parameters.
  :long-method — function body exceeds ~30-40 lines.
  :god-function — does too many unrelated things.
  :feature-envy — mostly operates on another object's data.
  :magic-numbers — unexplained numeric literals.
  :mutation-heavy — excessive mutable state manipulation.
  :global-state — reads/writes mutable global or static state.
  :duplication — contains copy-pasted or near-duplicate logic.
  :poor-naming — unclear, misleading, or inconsistent names.
  :dead-code — unreachable branches, unused parameters.
  :complex-conditional — long or deeply nested boolean expressions.

:purpose — one-line plain-English description of what this segment does (under 200 chars).

:safety-concerns — only include if you see a concrete issue in the code:
  :sql-injection — unsanitized input in SQL queries.
  :xss — unescaped user content in HTML output.
  :race-condition — shared mutable state without synchronization.
  :unsafe-cast — unchecked type cast that could fail at runtime.
  :path-traversal — unsanitized file path from user input.
  :command-injection — unsanitized input in shell commands.
  :buffer-overflow — out-of-bounds memory access (C/C++).
  :deserialization — deserializing untrusted data (pickle, Java serialization).
  :hardcoded-secret — credentials, API keys, or tokens in source.
  :insecure-random — using non-cryptographic random for security purposes.
  :unvalidated-redirect — redirect URL from user input without validation.

:error-handling — how well errors/exceptions are handled:
  :none — no error handling; exceptions propagate uncaught.
  :basic — some try/catch or error checks, but incomplete (e.g., swallows exceptions, broad catches).
  :robust — comprehensive handling with specific error types, proper logging/recovery.
  Omit for segments where error handling is not applicable.

:call-names — list of function/method names this segment calls. Use unqualified names (e.g. \"map\", \"connect\", \"fetch-data\"). Include ALL calls to functions/methods defined in the same project — these are used to build a call graph. Omit standard library and third-party calls (e.g. omit \"println\", \"str\", \"map\") unless they are project-defined. Omit if none.

:pure — true if the segment is side-effect-free: no I/O (file, network, database), no mutation of external state, no global state access. Pure functions depend only on their arguments and return a value. Omit if not pure or if unsure.

:ai-likelihood — assess whether this segment was likely written by an AI coding assistant:
  :likely-ai — strong AI signals: overly uniform formatting, boilerplate comments (\\\"Here is a function that...\\\"), excessive documentation relative to complexity, lack of idiomatic shortcuts, templated structure.
  :possibly-ai — some AI signals but inconclusive.
  :likely-human — idiomatic, terse, uses language-specific conventions, has organic variable naming and structure.
  :unknown — cannot determine (e.g., generated code, very short, or ambiguous).
  Omit if :likely-human (the default assumption)."

